nsexec: make the oom_score_adj write non-fatal.

nsexec writes /proc/self/oom_score_adj (an OOM-kill priority hint). On
this kernel that write fails with EACCES, and nsexec treats it as fatal,
so no sysbox container can start ("waiting for our first child to exit:
exit status 1"). Observed separately: lowering oom_score_adj is denied
inside a user namespace (raising is allowed; root outside one can lower
it). The value is non-essential, so warn and continue instead of aborting.

--- a/sysbox-runc/libcontainer/nsenter/nsexec.c
+++ b/sysbox-runc/libcontainer/nsenter/nsexec.c
@@ -350,7 +350,10 @@
 		return;
 
 	if (write_file(data, len, "/proc/self/oom_score_adj") < 0)
-		bail("failed to update /proc/self/oom_score_adj");
+		/* Non-fatal: oom_score_adj is only an OOM-kill priority hint, but on
+		 * this kernel the write is rejected with EACCES, which otherwise
+		 * aborts container startup. Warn and continue. */
+		write_log(WARNING, "failed to update /proc/self/oom_score_adj: %m");
 }
 
 /* A dummy function that just jumps to the given jumpval. */
